Key Findings:

Patient Characteristics
The dataset included lung cancer patients with varying ages, survival times, and clinical characteristics.
Age distribution analysis showed that lung cancer occurred across a wide range of adult age groups, with many patients being older adults.

Survival Time Analysis
Survival times varied substantially among patients.
Some patients had shorter survival periods, while others survived considerably longer, demonstrating differences in disease progression and patient characteristics.

Gender Differences
Kaplan-Meier survival analysis was used to compare survival probabilities between male and female patients.
The survival curves showed differences between groups, suggesting that demographic factors may influence survival outcomes.

Clinical Factors
The Cox proportional hazards model evaluated how factors such as:

Age
Gender
ECOG performance status
were associated with survival risk.

ECOG performance status was an important clinical indicator because a patient's functional status can influence treatment outcomes and overall prognosis.

3. Healthcare Significance
Survival analysis methods are valuable tools in healthcare analytics because they allow researchers and clinicians to study patient outcomes over time.
Understanding factors associated with survival can support:
Earlier identification of high-risk patients
Better treatment planning
Improved resource allocation
Evidence-based clinical decision-making

4. Limitations
The dataset contains a limited number of patients and may not represent all lung cancer populations.
Some clinical variables contained missing information, which required removing incomplete records.
The analysis identifies associations but does not prove causation.
Additional factors such as treatment type, smoking history, genetics, and comorbidities could provide further insight.



